<span class="type">Solution</span> <span class="acro">MM.C30</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.chrisblack.knowl">Chris Black</a></span>
</h5>$A^2 = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 4\\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}$,
$A^3 = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 6\\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}$,
$A^4 = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 8\\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}$.
From this pattern, we see that
$A^n = \begin{bmatrix}1 &amp; 2n\\ 0 &amp; 1\end{bmatrix}$.
